# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: luxon-datetime
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC has been widely embraced by most countries and is the effective successor to Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) in everyday usage and common applications.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In specialised domains such as scientific research, navigation, and timekeeping, other standards, such as UT1 and International Atomic Time (TAI), are also used alongside UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC is based on TAI (International Atomic Time, abbreviated from its French name, *temps atomique international*), which is a weighted average of hundreds of atomic clocks worldwide.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC is within about one second of mean solar time at 0° longitude, the currently used prime meridian, and is not adjusted for daylight saving time.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The coordination of time and frequency transmissions around the world began on 1 January 1960.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC was first officially adopted as a standard in 1963 and "UTC" became the official abbreviation of Coordinated Universal Time in 1967.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The current version of UTC is defined by the International Telecommunication Union.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Since adoption, UTC has been adjusted several times, notably adding leap seconds starting in 1972.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Recent years have seen significant developments in the realm of UTC, particularly in discussions about eliminating leap seconds from the timekeeping system because leap seconds occasionally disrupt timekeeping systems worldwide.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 2022 the General Conference on Weights and Measures adopted a resolution to alter UTC with a new system that would eliminate leap seconds by 2035.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The official abbreviation for Coordinated Universal Time is *UTC*.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This abbreviation comes as a result of the International Telecommunication Union and the International Astronomical Union wanting to use the same abbreviation in all languages.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The compromise that emerged was *UTC*, which conforms to the pattern for the abbreviations of the variants of Universal Time (UT0, UT1, UT2, UT1R, etc.).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Time zones around the world are expressed using positive, zero, or negative offsets from UTC, as in the list of time zones by UTC offset.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The westernmost time zone uses UTC−12, being twelve hours behind UTC; the easternmost time zone uses UTC+14, being fourteen hours ahead of UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1995, the island nation of Kiribati moved those of its atolls in the Line Islands from UTC−10 to UTC+14 so that the islands and atolls of Kiribati would all be on the same day.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC is used in many Internet and World Wide Web standards.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The Network Time Protocol (NTP), designed to synchronise the clocks of computers over the Internet, transmits time information from the UTC system.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] If only milliseconds precision is needed, clients can obtain the current UTC from a number of official internet UTC servers.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] For sub-microsecond precision, clients can obtain the time from satellite signals.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC is also the time standard used in aviation, e.g. for flight plans and air traffic control.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In this context it is frequently referred to as Zulu time, as described below.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Weather forecasts and maps all use UTC to avoid confusion about time zones and daylight saving time.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The International Space Station also uses UTC as a time standard.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Amateur radio operators often schedule their radio contacts in UTC, because transmissions on some frequencies can be picked up in many time zones.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC divides time into days, hours, minutes, and seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Days are conventionally identified using the Gregorian calendar, but Julian day numbers can also be used.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Each day contains 24 hours and each hour contains 60 minutes.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The number of seconds in a minute is usually 60, but with an occasional leap second, it may be 61 or 59 instead.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Thus, in the UTC time scale, the second and all smaller time units (millisecond, microsecond, etc.) are of constant duration, but the minute and all larger time units (hour, day, week, etc.) are of variable duration.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Decisions to introduce a leap second are announced at least six months in advance in "Bulletin C" produced by the International Earth Rotation and Reference Systems Service.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The leap seconds cannot be predicted far in advance due to the unpredictable rate of the rotation of Earth.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Nearly all UTC days contain exactly 86,400 SI seconds with exactly 60 seconds in each minute.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC is within about one second of mean solar time (such as UT1) at 0° longitude, (at the IERS Reference Meridian).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The mean solar day is slightly longer than 86,400 SI seconds so occasionally the last minute of a UTC day is adjusted to have 61 seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The extra second is called a leap second.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] It accounts for the grand total of the extra length (about 2 milliseconds each) of all the mean solar days since the previous leap second.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The last minute of a UTC day is permitted to contain 59 seconds to cover the remote possibility of the Earth rotating faster, but that has not yet been necessary.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The irregular day lengths mean fractional Julian days do not work properly with UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Since 1972, UTC may be calculated by subtracting the accumulated leap seconds from International Atomic Time (TAI), which is a coordinate time scale tracking notional proper time on the rotating surface of the Earth (the geoid).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In order to maintain a close approximation to UT1, UTC occasionally has discontinuities where it changes from one linear function of TAI to another.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] These discontinuities take the form of leap seconds implemented by a UTC day of irregular length.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Discontinuities in UTC occurred only at the end of June or December.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] However, there is provision for them to happen at the end of March and September as a second preference as well.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The International Earth Rotation and Reference Systems Service (IERS) tracks and publishes the difference between UTC and Universal Time, DUT1 = UT1 − UTC, and introduces discontinuities into UTC to keep DUT1 in the interval (−0.9 s, +0.9 s).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] As with TAI, UTC is only known with the highest precision in retrospect.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Users who require an approximation in real time must obtain it from a time laboratory, which disseminates an approximation using techniques such as GPS or radio time signals.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Such approximations are designated UTC(*k*), where *k* is an abbreviation for the time laboratory.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Because of time dilation, a standard clock not on the geoid, or in rapid motion, will not maintain synchronicity with UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Therefore, telemetry from clocks with a known relation to the geoid is used to provide UTC when required, on locations such as those of spacecraft.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] It is impossible to compute the exact time interval elapsed between two UTC timestamps without consulting a table showing how many leap seconds occurred during that interval.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] By extension, it is not possible to compute the precise duration of a time interval that ends in the future and may encompass an unknown number of leap seconds (for example, the number of TAI seconds between "now" and 2099-12-31 23:59:59).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Therefore, many scientific applications that require precise measurement of long (multi-year) intervals use TAI instead.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] TAI is also commonly used by systems that cannot handle leap seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] GPS time always remains exactly 19 seconds behind TAI (neither system is affected by the leap seconds introduced in UTC).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Time zones are usually defined as differing from UTC by an integer number of hours, although the laws of each jurisdiction would have to be consulted if sub-second accuracy were required.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Several jurisdictions have established time zones that differ by an odd number of half-hours or quarter-hours from UT1 or UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Current civil time in a particular time zone can be determined by adding or subtracting the number of hours and minutes specified by the UTC offset, which ranges from UTC−12:00 in the west to UTC+14:00 in the east (see List of UTC offsets).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The time zone using UTC is sometimes denoted UTC+00:00 or by the letter *Z*—a reference to the equivalent nautical time zone (GMT), which has been denoted by a *Z* since about 1950.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Time zones were identified by successive letters of the alphabet and the Greenwich time zone was marked by a *Z* as it was the point of origin.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The letter also refers to the "zone description" of zero hours, which has been used since 1920 (see time zone history).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Since the NATO phonetic alphabet word for *Z* is "Zulu", UTC is sometimes known as "**Zulu time**".
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This is especially true in aviation, where "Zulu" is the universal standard.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This ensures that all pilots, regardless of location, are using the same 24-hour clock, thus avoiding confusion when flying between time zones.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] See the list of military time zones for letters used in addition to *Z* in qualifying time zones other than Greenwich.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC does not change with a change of seasons, but local time or civil time may change if a time zone jurisdiction observes daylight saving time (summer time).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] For example, local time on the east coast of the United States is five hours behind UTC during winter, but four hours behind while daylight saving is observed there.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1928, the term *Universal Time* (*UT*) was introduced by the International Astronomical Union to refer to GMT, with the day starting at midnight.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Until the 1950s, broadcast time signals were based on UT, and hence on the rotation of the Earth.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1955, the caesium atomic clock was invented.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This provided a form of timekeeping that was both more stable and more convenient than astronomical observations.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Naval Observatory started to develop atomic frequency time scales; by 1959, these time scales were used in generating the WWV time signals, named for the shortwave radio station that broadcasts them.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Naval Observatory, the Royal Greenwich Observatory, and the UK National Physical Laboratory coordinated their radio broadcasts so that time steps and frequency changes were coordinated, and the resulting time scale was informally referred to as "Coordinated Universal Time".
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In a controversial decision, the frequency of the signals was initially set to match the rate of UT, but then kept at the same frequency by the use of atomic clocks and deliberately allowed to drift away from UT.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] When the divergence grew significantly, the signal was phase shifted (stepped) by 20 ms to bring it back into agreement with UT.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Twenty-nine such steps were used before 1960.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1958, data was published linking the frequency for the caesium transition, newly established, with the ephemeris second.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The ephemeris second is a unit in the system of time that, when used as the independent variable in the laws of motion that govern the movement of the planets and moons in the Solar System, enables the laws of motion to accurately predict the observed positions of Solar System bodies.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Within the limits of observable accuracy, ephemeris seconds are of constant length, as are atomic seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This publication allowed a value to be chosen for the length of the atomic second that would accord with the celestial laws of motion.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC was first officially adopted in 1963 as CCIR Recommendation 374, *Standard-Frequency and Time-Signal Emissions*, and "UTC" became the official abbreviation of Coordinated Universal Time in 1967.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1961, the Bureau International de l'Heure began coordinating the UTC process internationally (but the name Coordinated Universal Time was not formally adopted by the International Astronomical Union until 1967).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] From then on, there were time steps every few months, and frequency changes at the end of each year.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The jumps increased in size to 0.1 seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This UTC was intended to permit a very close approximation to UT2.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1967, the SI second was redefined in terms of the frequency supplied by a caesium atomic clock.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The length of second so defined was practically equal to the second of ephemeris time.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This was the frequency that had been provisionally used in TAI since 1958.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] It was soon decided that having two types of second with different lengths, namely the UTC second and the SI second used in TAI, was a bad idea.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] It was thought better for time signals to maintain a consistent frequency, and that this frequency should match the SI second.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Thus it would be necessary to rely on time steps alone to maintain the approximation of UT.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This was tried experimentally in a service known as "Stepped Atomic Time" (SAT), which ticked at the same rate as TAI and used jumps of 0.2 seconds to stay synchronised with UT2.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] There was also dissatisfaction with the frequent jumps in UTC (and SAT).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 1968, Louis Essen, the inventor of the caesium atomic clock, and G.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Winkler both independently proposed that steps should be of 1 second only. to simplify future adjustments.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This system was eventually approved as leap seconds in a new UTC in 1970 and implemented in 1972, along with the idea of maintaining the UTC second equal to the TAI second.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] At the same time, the tick rate of UTC was changed to exactly match TAI.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC also started to track UT1 rather than UT2.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Some time signals started to broadcast the DUT1 correction (UT1 − UTC) for applications requiring a closer approximation of UT1 than UTC provided.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Leap seconds are inserted as necessary to keep UTC within 0.9 seconds of the UT1 variant of universal time.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] See § Current number of leap seconds for the number of leap seconds inserted to date.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The first leap second occurred on 30 June 1972.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Since then, leap seconds have occurred on average about once every 19 months, always on 30 June or 31 December.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] As of July 2022, there have been 27 leap seconds in total, all positive, putting UTC 37 seconds behind TAI.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] A study published in March 2024 in *Nature* found that accelerated melting of ice in Greenland and Antarctica due to climate change has slowed Earth's rotation enough to delay the next negative leap-second adjustment to UTC, postponing problems for computer systems.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Earth's rotational speed is very slowly decreasing because of tidal deceleration; this increases the length of the mean solar day.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The length of the SI second was calibrated on the basis of the second of ephemeris time and can now be seen to have a relationship with the mean solar day observed between 1750 and 1892, analysed by Simon Newcomb.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] As a result, the SI second is close to ⁠1/86400⁠ of a mean solar day in the mid‑19th century.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In earlier centuries, the mean solar day was shorter than 86,400 SI seconds, and in more recent centuries it is longer than 86,400 seconds.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Near the end of the 20th century, the length of the mean solar day (also known simply as "length of day" or "LOD") was approximately 86,400.0013 s.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] For this reason, UT is now "slower" than TAI by the difference (or "excess" LOD) of 1.3 ms/day.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The excess of the LOD over the nominal 86,400 s accumulates over time, causing the UTC day, initially synchronised with the mean sun, to become desynchronised and run ahead of it.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Near the end of the 20th century, with the LOD at 1.3 ms above the nominal value, UTC ran faster than UT by 1.3 ms per day, getting a second ahead roughly every 800 days.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Thus, leap seconds were inserted at approximately this interval, retarding UTC to keep it synchronised in the long term.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The actual rotational period varies on unpredictable factors such as tectonic motion and has to be observed, rather than computed.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Just as adding a leap day every four years does not mean the year is getting longer by one day every four years, the insertion of a leap second every 800 days does not indicate that the mean solar day is getting longer by a second every 800 days.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] It will take about 50,000 years for a mean solar day to lengthen by one second (at a rate of 2 ms per century).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This rate fluctuates within the range of 1.7–2.3 ms/cy.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] While the rate due to tidal friction alone is about 2.3 ms/cy, the uplift of Canada and Scandinavia by several metres since the last ice age has temporarily reduced this to 1.7 ms/cy over the last 2,700 years.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In the graph of DUT1 above, the excess of LOD above the nominal 86,400 s corresponds to the downward slope of the graph between vertical segments.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Leap seconds are timed to keep DUT1 within the vertical range depicted by the adjacent graph.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The frequency of leap seconds therefore corresponds to the slope of the diagonal graph segments, and thus to the excess LOD.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Time periods when the slope reverses direction (slopes upwards, not the vertical segments) are times when the excess LOD is negative, that is, when the LOD is below 86,400 s.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] As the Earth's rotation continues to slow, positive leap seconds will be required more frequently.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The long-term rate of change of LOD is approximately +1.7 ms per century.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] At the end of the 21st century, LOD will be roughly 86,400.004 s, requiring a leap second about every 250 days.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Over several centuries, the frequency of leap seconds will become problematic.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] A change in the trend of the UT1 − UTC values was seen beginning around June 2019 in which instead of slowing down (with leap seconds to keep the difference between UT1 and UTC less than 0.9 seconds) the Earth's rotation has sped up, causing this difference to increase.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] If the trend continues, a negative leap second may be required, which has not been used before.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Some time in the 22nd century, two leap seconds will be required every year.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The current practice of only allowing leap seconds in June and December will be insufficient to maintain a difference of less than 1 second, and it might be decided to introduce leap seconds in March and September.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In the 25th century, four leap seconds are projected to be required every year, so the current quarterly options would be insufficient.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In April 2001, Rob Seaman of the National Optical Astronomy Observatory proposed that leap seconds be allowed to be added monthly rather than twice yearly.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] In 2022 a resolution was adopted by the General Conference on Weights and Measures to redefine UTC and abolish leap seconds, but keep the civil second constant and equal to the SI second, so that sundials would slowly get further and further out of sync with civil time.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The leap seconds will be eliminated by 2035.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The resolution does not break the connection between UTC and UT1, but increases the maximum allowable difference.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The details of what the maximum difference will be and how corrections will be implemented is left for future discussions.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This will result in a shift of the sun's movements relative to civil time, with the difference increasing quadratically with time (i.e., proportional to elapsed centuries squared).
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This is analogous to the shift of seasons relative to the yearly calendar that results from the calendar year not precisely matching the tropical year length.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This would be a change in civil timekeeping, and would have a slow effect at first but become drastic over several centuries.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] UTC (and TAI) would be more and more ahead of UT; it would coincide with local mean time along a meridian drifting eastward faster and faster.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] Thus, the time system will lose its fixed connection to the geographic coordinates based on the IERS meridian.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] The difference between UTC and UT would reach 0.5 hours after the year 2600 and 6.5 hours around 4600.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] This conference, in turn, considered the question, but no permanent decision was reached; it only chose to engage in further study with the goal of reconsideration in 2023.
[src:luxon-datetime/coordinated-universal-time] A proposed alternative to the leap second is the leap hour or leap minute, which requires changes only once every few centuries.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] The **`Intl.DateTimeFormat`** object enables language-sensitive date and time formatting.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] Creates a new `Intl.DateTimeFormat` object.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] Returns an array containing those of the provided locales that are supported without having to fall back to the runtime's default locale.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] These properties are defined on `Intl.DateTimeFormat.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.DateTimeFormat` instances.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] For `Intl.DateTimeFormat` instances, the initial value is the `Intl.DateTimeFormat` constructor.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Intl.DateTimeFormat"`.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] Getter function that formats a date according to the locale and formatting options of this `DateTimeFormat` object.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] This method receives two Dates and formats the date range in the most concise way based on the locale and options provided when instantiating `DateTimeFormat`.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] This method receives two Dates and returns an Array of objects containing the locale-specific tokens representing each part of the formatted date range.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] Returns an `Array` of objects representing the date string in parts that can be used for custom locale-aware formatting.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and formatting options computed during initialization of the object.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] In basic use without specifying a locale, `DateTimeFormat` uses the default locale and default options.
[src:luxon-datetime/datetimeformat] This example shows some of the variations in localized date and time formats.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] JavaScript **`Date`** objects represent a single moment in time in a platform-independent format.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date` objects encapsulate an integral number that represents milliseconds since the midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC (the *epoch*).
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] A JavaScript date is fundamentally specified as the time in milliseconds that has elapsed since the epoch, which is defined as the midnight at the beginning of January 1, 1970, UTC (equivalent to the UNIX epoch).
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] This timestamp is *timezone-agnostic* and uniquely defines an instant in history.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The maximum timestamp representable by a `Date` object is slightly smaller than the maximum safe integer (`Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`, which is 9,007,199,254,740,991).
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] This is the range from April 20, 271821 BC to September 13, 275760 AD.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Any attempt to represent a time outside this range results in the `Date` object holding a timestamp value of `NaN`, which is an "Invalid Date".
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] A date is represented internally as a single number, the *timestamp*.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] When interacting with it, the timestamp needs to be interpreted as a structured date-and-time representation.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] There are always two ways to interpret a timestamp: as a local time or as a Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the global standard time defined by the World Time Standard.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The local timezone is not stored in the date object, but is determined by the host environment (user's device).
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The `getTimezoneOffset()` method returns the difference between UTC and the local time in minutes.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Note that the timezone offset does not only depend on the current timezone, but also on the time represented by the `Date` object, because of daylight saving time and historical changes.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] In essence, the timezone offset is the offset from UTC time, at the time represented by the `Date` object and at the location of the host environment.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] There are two groups of `Date` methods: one group gets and sets various date components by interpreting the timestamp as a local time, while the other uses UTC.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The `Date()` constructor can be called with two or more arguments, in which case they are interpreted as the year, month, day, hour, minute, second, and millisecond, respectively, in local time.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date.UTC()` works similarly, but it interprets the components as UTC time and also accepts a single argument representing the year.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] When a segment overflows or underflows its expected range, it usually "carries over to" or "borrows from" the higher segment.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] For example, if the month is set to 12 (months are zero-based, so December is 11), it becomes the January of the next year.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] If the day of month is set to 0, it becomes the last day of the previous month.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] This also applies to dates specified with the date time string format.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] When attempting to set the local time to a time falling within an offset transition (usually daylight saving time), the exact time is derived using the same behavior as `Temporal`'s `disambiguation: "compatible"` option.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] That is, if the local time corresponds to two instants, the earlier one is chosen; if the local time does not exist (there is a gap), we go forward by the gap duration.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] There are many ways to format a date as a string.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The JavaScript specification only specifies one format to be universally supported: the *date time string format*, a simplification of the ISO 8601 calendar date extended format.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] When the time zone offset is absent, **date-only forms are interpreted as a UTC time and date-time forms are interpreted as a local time.** The interpretation as a UTC time is due to a historical spec error that was not consistent with ISO 8601 but could not be changed due to web compatibility.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] See Broken Parser – A Web Reality Issue.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] `Date.parse()` and the `Date()` constructor both accept strings in the date time string format as input.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Furthermore, implementations are allowed to support other date formats when the input fails to match this format.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The `toISOString()` method returns a string representation of the date in the date time string format, with the time zone offset always set to `Z` (UTC).
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Non-standard strings can be parsed in any way as desired by the implementation, including the time zone — most implementations use the local time zone by default.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Implementations are not required to return invalid date for out-of-bounds date components, although they usually do.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] A string may have in-bounds date components (with the bounds defined above), but does not represent a date in reality (for example, "February 30").
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] Implementations behave inconsistently in this case.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] The `Date.parse()` page offers more examples about these non-standard cases.
[src:luxon-datetime/global-objects-date] See the Formats of `toString` method return values section for examples.
